segments.text: Can you tell me anything since you've been here?
Have you had any bad droughts or heavy rains that have really hurt the Bryan-Claude Station area that you know of?
Oh, not anything catastrophic that I know of.
And heavy rains coming in here messed up the bomber at different times.
There's been a hell of a lot of dry weather all along.
But not, you know, we haven't had any floods to speak of.
You know, we've had floods in Bryan.
You know, we've got some out in Carter Creek and some places like this.
Nothing major.
You don't have any...
The effects of any hurricanes that hit the coast.
One that never bothered me while we were here was the one that borrowed my house.
It's a two.
It's a two.
And it was lucky.
That's when we got all the people from the coast.
People put them up in their homes.
When I was back when I was young, I had a Jason.
And we set up all these.
Have you ever had any
I can't really say big.
When it comes to election time, like you're fixing to have one, can you ever remember one year or so when it was really important?
It's important every time.
When the people really got involved.
But when the people really get involved.
Nowadays, most people don't get involved in politics.
Most elections, they won't go out and vote.
Can you mirror any time where people really were serious about it?
Oh, yeah.
In the city election, I remember back here, and I can't remember the year, but it's probably been six, seven years ago.
Six, seven.
When the people of Bryan probably got more involved in the city election than they ever did at any time, that's when they had a slated option that we all thought we were going to get elected.
Again, talking about the legislature, we were all backing it on, and they all got defeated.
And the common man, George said, yes, we've got an office.
Probably did about as good a job as any city council member.
He's still in office?
The whole slate hasn't gotten off.
That's back when they elected the city commission and they elected their own mayor out of their group.
They had the mayor and council.
And they elected five of them each time.
And they elected that slate five times.
There was some good people, huh?
Both sides.
It kind of shocked everybody.
A year ago, the mayor's race was real close.
I had a lot of people involved.
That's what Laura Jones was doing.
Does Brian have a city manager form of government?
Or is he the
Is the head or is the mayor?
No.
Brian has the mayor and council.
No city manager.
And they have a city manager who manages them.
The mayor and council are, they run it.
But the city manager administers it.
Brian Mayer, I think, makes $10 a month.
The council makes $1 a month.
Something like that.
Well, the city manager makes $4 a month.
They do have cities where that's why I just want to make sure.
Has there ever been a thought where they want to change the system?
The city manager might be over the mayor?
No.
Now, I don't think it works.
I don't think it works.
Have you ever had any, this is going again on politics and all, have you ever had any problems or any issues about rezoning the city?
I've had quite an issue twice since I've been here.
And I would like to be in to some extent, I guess.
About zoning, period.
I have no zoning.
You have no zoning?
I have no zoning.
I was bothered on the building down here.
What do you think?
Is Bryan College Station very bad on ethnic discrimination?
Where you're going to a restaurant, they make the blacks sit in one room and all there's nothing.
They treat everybody as equal.
We have blacks living all over.
And that's how you live in everything.
I know.
Just down Columbus.
It's pretty bad.
Small town.
I'm sure.
I don't know.
I'm sure.
We have a black movie about what house not suddenly just started.
Sure should be up.
What do you think we can do about it?
I didn't care if you lived out there.
I don't live there anyway, so.
But what, you know, I was upset about the thing that was going to affect selling our houses.
And we sold several custom houses to people.
So I went to every one of them and told them.
The black blooded in there.
I didn't want to have trouble then, you know.
We got the thing built.
They wanted out of contact with me out there.
We had not won.
Perfectly.
I swear.
It's strange.
A man threw a gas gun at me.
Oh, he asked me, he said, would you tell him to gas that man?
I said, I don't want to get any food.
I think...
Racial discrimination behind the dollar station is certainly not bad.
I don't see it as bad.
I don't see what I'm doing.
I know the off-street block people come down here and they disagree to hell with me.
I know the blacks and the Chicano's.
But they're qualified.
I think we'll all hire them.
We can't find them qualified.
And we can't hire hard-hitting blacks anymore.
Now, on our construction jobs 10 years ago, we had all kind of blacks.
And the only one that we've got now is our plumber.
He's a contractor.
He's probably the best plumber contractor I've ever had work with.
I think as much as any man works for him.
But he's the only one.
He's not out there.
It's hard to find a job here.
No, it's hard to find somebody to work here.
We'd put anybody to work if they had work right now.
I heard there wasn't too many jobs here.
What would you define?
Construction?
Well, not only construction, anything in general.
Anything to make a living.
A man want to work in this town, he can get a job and make a living.
He can.
He doesn't have to go to Houston or Dallas.
She'd go down there, and I'm not out here on that.
You can talk and say, yeah, there's some boys, boys, biggies.
I'm going to be a biggie.
But I know for a fact she'd go to the son and text the father.
I promise I know a boy down there going down to the father and make sure the job will be tight.
And why they keep paying them down to the father, I don't know, and they work.
But that's a fact.
They don't know how to do anything.
Anything they're qualified to do.
But we can't hire them.
That's my parents.
Yeah.
It's pretty interesting.
Do you think, going back just a little bit, back to the college, do you think, what do you think about the football team?
Is that affected?
people around her in the spirit.
Whereas everybody talks about the football team.
I've never seen so much advertisement to go up to a Ramada Inn in Texas Avenue and after every fire they have to post up the scores.
During the fall of the year, this community is
Tied up almost 100% in that Texas A&M football.
They're pretty proud of the team.
That's right.
They're like football fans, I guess, the world over.
We had to see them get weak.
I'm not angry with them.
I'm on the opposite end, I guess, like all of you.
Had a 10-2 season last year.
One of the better records in the country.
But you don't hear much good about football, do you?
They lost those last two games, of course.
The Aggie fans aren't all bad, I guess.
They like to win.
Of course, I understand you can't get tickets out of the National League.
I like the spirit of Aggieland.
It's great.
I'm sure a lot of people don't like football, but it's all good.
Off the top of your head.
Do you think that attracts people moving here?
Okay.
I'm going to round this off now.
Is there anything else that you want to add?
You asked it earlier.
I thank you for calling me.
I appreciate it and so forth.
Hey, look.
uh... uh... uh...
And I don't think anyone in the world, the committee,
It's too much for the city to afford.
That's right.
And we've got a bond collection tomorrow.
A revenue bond against the dam, the power plant, and so forth.
Empty thing.
There's a city on the opposite of private enterprise.
That's a bond issue.
Now what are they going to do after this thing?
Fifteen million dollars so far in their sales.
The law wouldn't be in place.
They don't get more bond money than they do.
Just by talking to people, do you think they voted against it or for it?
I thought it was a package.
But I haven't talked to a lot of them.
But the working class people, they've come up with a vote.
The bond issue, they've been defeated a lot more than the people last two years in the past.
You know, we had this blue ribbon on the ground.
If all these plans of Brian May's have been with College Station, and they jump up into College Station, they look good, but they're down.
I mean, they're not prepared for dusting.
At the College Station, it's pretty good-sized dusting.
And so that may affect this bond issue, but people think, you know, these College Station don't need that power plant.
What's the need?
We've got that power plant.
We're old.
We get old with it.
They're not an issue.
But I think probably that is the biggest problem with saving lives in the future.
Well, I sure do appreciate it.
I hope I helped you.
Okay, thank you.
